        <!-- BLOG CONTENT -->
        <div class="article-layout">
            <!-- TABLE OF CONTENTS -->
            <aside class="table-of-contents">
                <nav class="toc-nav">
                    <!-- <h3 class="toc-title">Table of Contents</h3> -->
                    <ul class="toc-list">
                        <li class="toc-item">
                            <a href="#core-problem" class="toc-link active"
                                >The Core Problem: Astro Wasn't...</a
                            >
                        </li>
                        <li class="toc-item">
                            <a href="#generic-libraries" class="toc-link"
                                >Why Generic Animation Libraries...</a
                            >
                        </li>
                        <li class="toc-item">
                            <a href="#astro-needs" class="toc-link"
                                >What Astro Actually Needs From...</a
                            >
                        </li>
                        <li class="toc-item">
                            <a href="#what-is-astroanimate" class="toc-link"
                                >What is AstroAnimate?</a
                            >
                        </li>
                        <li class="toc-item">
                            <a href="#architecture" class="toc-link"
                                >How AstroAnimate Differs Architectur...</a
                            >
                        </li>
                        <li class="toc-item">
                            <a href="#css-first" class="toc-link"
                                >CSS-First Design: Why It Matters</a
                            >
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </nav>
            </aside>

            <!-- MAIN CONTENT -->
            <article class="article-body">
                <section id="core-problem" class="content-section">
                    <h2>
                        Why Astro Needs a Dedicated Animation Library (And How
                        AstroAnimate Solves It)
                    </h2>
                    <p>Astro is static-first and built around Islands Architecture. Most animation libraries assume fully hydrated client frameworks, which expands bundle size and breaks performance boundaries.</p>
<p>AstroAnimate is a dedicated Astro animation library designed specifically for Astro. It provides CSS-first primitives, optional JS adapters, and built-in Astro View Transitions compatibility without forcing global hydration.</p>
                    <h3>
                        The Core Problem: Astro Wasn’t Designed for Client-Heavy Animation
                    </h3>
                    <p>
                        Astro is not a fully client-rendered framework.
Astro renders static HTML by default and hydrates only what you explicitly opt into. That architectural decision changes how animation should be implemented.
                    </p>
                    <p>Most animation libraries were built assuming:</p>

                    <ul class="content-list">
                        <li>
                            <span class="diamond"></span>

                            Full client-side runtime
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="diamond"></span>
Persistent hydration
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="diamond"></span>
                          Global initialization
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="diamond"></span>
                           Virtual DOM orchestration
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>Astro was designed to avoid those assumptions. That mismatch creates friction.
For example, importing a timeline-based animation library just to fade in a hero section can add tens of kilobytes of JavaScript and introduce unnecessary hydration. The effect works but the performance cost may not be justified.</p>
                </section>

                <section id="generic-libraries" class="content-section">
                    <h3>
                        Why Generic Animation Libraries Don’t Fit Astro Cleanly
                    </h3>
                    <p>
                        Libraries like GSAP, Motion, or AOS are powerful tools. They work well in client-rendered applications.
                    </p>

                    <p>In Astro, however, they typically require:</p>
                    <ul class="content-list">
                        <li>
                            <span class="diamond"></span>
                            Hydrated islands
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="diamond"></span>
                           Runtime execution
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="diamond"></span>
                            Expanded bundle size
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>When used without careful scoping, hydration boundaries grow quickly.
Astro’s philosophy is clear:</p>

<div class="blog-highlight-border">
    <p class="highlight-text">Ship as little JavaScript as possible.</p>
</div>
<p>Many animation libraries assume JavaScript is always present. Astro assumes it is optional.
That architectural difference matters.</p>
                </section>

                <section id="astro-needs" class="content-section">
                    <h3>What Astro Actually Needs From an Animation System</h3>
                    <p>
                        Astro needs motion that respects:
                    </p>

                    <ul class="content-list">
                        <li>
                            <span class="diamond"></span>
Static rendering                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="diamond"></span>
Islands Architecture                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="diamond"></span>
Hydration boundaries                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="diamond"></span>
Astro View Transitions                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="diamond"></span>
Performance budgets                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </section>

                <section id="what-is-astroanimate" class="content-section">
                    <h3>What is AstroAnimate?</h3>
                    <p>
                        AstroAnimate is a purpose-built animation library
                        designed specifically for Astro's unique architecture.
                        It provides powerful animation capabilities while
                        respecting Astro's core principles of performance and
                        minimal JavaScript.
                    </p>

                    <ul class="content-list">
                        <li>
                            <span class="diamond"></span>
                            CSS and Web Animations API based transitions
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="diamond"></span>
                            Zero runtime JavaScript unless explicitly enabled
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="diamond"></span>
                            Built for Islands architecture
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="diamond"></span>
                            Native View Transitions API support
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="diamond"></span>
                            Server-side rendering compatible
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </section>

                <section id="architecture" class="content-section">
                    <h3>How AstroAnimate Differs Architecturally</h3>
                    <p>
                        Unlike traditional animation libraries, AstroAnimate is
                        built around Astro's architectural patterns. It
                        understands Islands boundaries, respects server-side
                        rendering, and provides progressive enhancement.
                    </p>

                    <ul class="content-list">
                        <li>
                            <span class="diamond"></span>
                            Component-scoped animations that respect Island boundaries
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="diamond"></span>
                            CSS-based animations with JavaScript enhancement layers
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="diamond"></span>
                            View Transitions API as first-class citizen
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="diamond"></span>
                            Server-side animation state management
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="diamond"></span>
                            Progressive enhancement approach
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </section>

                <section id="css-first" class="content-section">
                    <h3>CSS-First Design: Why It Matters</h3>
                    <p>
                        The CSS-first approach is fundamental to AstroAnimate's
                        design. By prioritizing CSS animations and using
                        JavaScript only when necessary, we maintain Astro's
                        performance benefits while still providing rich
                        animation capabilities.
                    </p>

                    <ul class="content-list">
                        <li>
                            <span class="diamond"></span>
                            Better performance with CSS-only animations
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="diamond"></span>
                            Reduced JavaScript bundle size
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="diamond"></span>
                            Improved accessibility with reduced motion support
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="diamond"></span>
                            Server-side rendering compatibility
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <span class="diamond"></span>
                            Progressive enhancement capabilities
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </section>
            </article>

